There's a big connection, since the behavior of the objects determines
whether the collisions are elastic or inelastic (and to what degree, of
course, since it's a spectrum).  I pointed out what that connection is
in what you quoted above.  A very hard object tends to be involved in
elastic collisions (a pool ball).  A very springy object also tends to
be involved in elastic collisions (a very bouncy ball, as a kid we
called them &quot;superballs,&quot; not sure if that's a brand name or not).  An
object that deforms and remains deformed during a collision is
inelastic, since it absorbs some of the energy of the collision in the
process of deforming.

The two concepts are intimately related.  And you didn't address the
issue that pushing objects into one another -- what you were talking
about -- is by definition a collision.

