This has absolutely nothing to do with what I meant
when I said collisions with Spherical Cows are always
perfectly inelastic.  To simplify physics modeling,
Spherical Cow collisions are all either perfectly elastic
or perfectly inelastic--meaning either Spherical Cows
bounce with 100% kinetic energy retention or they
always bounce with minimum kinetic energy retention
(converting the kinetic energy balance into heat which
is a monolithic statistic of the Spherical Cow--it's treated
as a single molecule for thermal modeling purposes).

Real life cows don't bounce very high when they fall
from a great height.  Instead, they pretty much don't
bounce at all.  Therefore, a Spherical Cow don't
bounce at all--their collisions are perfectly inelastic.

As for plasticity or ductility or Young's Modulus or
anything else to do with deformation--Spherical Cows
don't deform.  They are perfectly spherical.

